amentas de educação online crescendo exponencialmente em todo mundo, e uma geração de pessoas que prefere vídeos curtos do Youtube a assistir um filme ou uma aula de 45 minutos, abre-se uma perspectiva enorme de trazermos as empresas de TI em contato com esses jovens através da internet, invertendo o modelo de atração e capacitação de talentos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Precisamos nos conscientizar de que o caminho do crescimento tecnológico é um caminho sem volta, e que temos a obrigação como sociedade de não deixar que o Brasil fique de fora de mais essa revolução mundial.</p>\r\n','Indústria de TI terá 160 mil vagas não preenchidas em 2014','','inherit','open','open','','391-revision-v1','','','2014-01-10 10:35:18','2014-01-10 10:35:18','',391,'http://www.talento-labs.com/uncategorized/391-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(348,2,'2013-12-09 22:13:34','2013-12-09 22:13:34','<a href=\"http://www.talento-labs.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/futebol-de-rua-leo-lima-texto_650.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-345\" alt=\"futebol-de-rua-leo-lima-texto_650\" src=\"http://www.talento-labs.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/futebol-de-rua-leo-lima-texto_650-300x200.jpg\" width=\"650px\"/></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe global educational model is changing rapidly. The most advanced economies are changing the way in which students come out of university and enter the job market.\r\n\r\nBut the European and American models of adapting the curriculum of reputable universities and putting them online isn’t disruptive enough and it’s not compatible with the reality of Brazil: a country where so many young people have no access to internet, much less contact with the corporate world.\r\n\r\nThere is, however, a model of identification and training of talent that is very Brazilian and has a lot more probability of being successful in our environment: the way of the football clubs.\r\n\r\nBrazilian football clubs are arguably the best in the world in sourcing talent, spreading scouters all over the country, using the attractiveness of their brands to identify and bring in potential talent. But they don’t stop at scouting: there are several football academies all over the Brazilian territory, where coaches designated by the clubs work on teaching kids fundamental football skills, training them to become future professional players, forming a web system of identification, attraction and training of young football talent.\r\n\r\nWe all know that, just as there are people who are born with the spatial intelligence to become football players, many of us are born with the logical intelligence that will make for great programmers. And in Brazil we’re literally wasting all those people, which is not only bad for them, but it’s disastrous for the country.\r\n\r\nTo compete globally and grow, Brazil will need to upgrade its know-how in technology, which is at an abysmal rate today, mainly for our lack of talent in the area.\r\n\r\nThe good news though is that today it’s extremely cheap to spread programming academies all over the country, using state of the art computing technology and the best educational software available.\r\n\r\nLarge IT companies need talent now more than ever, and they spend entire fortunes in recruitment and training techniques, many of which can be considered outdated. Brazilian universities are expensive, hard to get to for people in these communities and aren’t at a good level of education. It’s the perfect scenario for building IT academies, where talent are sponsored and trained by these companies.\r\n\r\nThere are very few programs in lower income communities that are focused on higher achieving careers, and there’s no reason to think that they don’t have the talent needed to develop the necessary skills.\r\n\r\nMany of the world’s best programmers are self-taught, which means that much like football, programming is a talent that needs only to be developed. And the best of all is that IT talent can achieve greatness in large or small companies, being a freelancer or an entrepreneur, and it’s open to both men and women.','Adapting Football’s Talent Sourcing Model in IT','','publish','open','open','','adapting-footballs-talent-sourcing-model-in-it','','','2013-12-15 17:55:28','2013-12-15 17:55:28','',0,'http://www.talento-labs.com/?p=348',0,'post','',0),(349,2,'2013-12-09 22:13:34','2013-12-09 22:13:34','<a href=\"http://www.talento-labs.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/futebol-de-rua-leo-lima-texto_650.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-345\" alt=\"futebol-de-rua-leo-lima-texto_650\" src=\"http://www.talento-labs.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/futebol-de-rua-leo-lima-texto_650-300x200.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe global educational model is changing rapidly. The most advanced economies are changing the way in which students come out of university and enter the job market.\r\n\r\nBut the European and American models of adapting the curriculum of reputable universities and putting them online isn’t disruptive enough and it’s not compatible with the reality of Brazil: a country where so many young people have no access to internet, much less contact with the corporate world.\r\n\r\nThere is, however, a model of identification and training of talent that is very Brazilian and has a lot more probability of being successful in our environment: the way of the football clubs.\r\n\r\nBrazilian football clubs are arguably the best in the world in sourcing talent, spreading scouters all over the country, using the attractiveness of their brands to identify and bring in potential talent. But they don’t stop at scouting: there are several football academies all over the Brazilian territory, where coaches designated by the clubs work on teaching kids fundamental football skills, training them to become future professional players, forming a web system of identification, attraction and training of young football talent.\r\n\r\nWe all know that, just 